1
00:02:28,781 --> 00:02:30,681
<i>Typical of Victor Von Doom</i>

2
00:02:30,783 --> 00:02:33,684
to build a 30-foot statue
of himself.

3
00:02:33,786 --> 00:02:37,745
Well, it's obviously aimed at first-time visitors
to create feelings of smallness...

4
00:02:37,857 --> 00:02:39,757
inadequacy.

5
00:02:39,859 --> 00:02:43,022
Good thing
it ain't workin'.

6
00:02:43,129 --> 00:02:46,826
Reed, what are we doing here?
This guy's fast-food, strip-mall science.

7
00:02:46,933 --> 00:02:49,333
This wasn't our first stop,
in case you forgot.

8
00:02:49,435 --> 00:02:54,031
Besides, Victor's not that bad.
He's just a little... larger than life.

9
00:03:03,516 --> 00:03:08,044
- Hi, Reed Richards and Ben Grimm-
- Executive elevator. Top floor.

10
00:03:14,694 --> 00:03:17,891
What's it take to get
a smile around this joint?

11
00:03:17,997 --> 00:03:19,988
<i>[ Woman ]
<i>Von Doom Industries, at the forefront</i>

12
00:03:20,099 --> 00:03:23,227
<i>of aerospace technology</i>
<i>and biomedical engineering-</i>

13
00:03:23,336 --> 00:03:25,770
<i>The unparalleled leader</i>
<i>in government defense systems</i>

14
00:03:25,872 --> 00:03:27,772
<i>[ Reed ]
<i>My research suggests</i>

15
00:03:27,874 --> 00:03:30,274
that exposure to
a high-energy cosmic storm...

16
00:03:30,376 --> 00:03:32,276
borne
on solar winds...

17
00:03:32,378 --> 00:03:35,677
might have triggered the evolution
of early planetary life.

18
00:03:35,782 --> 00:03:37,500
In six weeks
another cloud...

19
00:03:37,500 --> 00:03:38,797
In six weeks another cloud...

20
00:03:38,900 --> 00:03:40,800
with the same elemental profile...

21
00:03:40,902 --> 00:03:43,200
will pass Earth's orbit.

22
00:03:43,305 --> 00:03:45,205
A study, conducted in space...

23
00:03:45,307 --> 00:03:47,207
could fundamentally advance
our knowledge...

24
00:03:47,309 --> 00:03:49,436
about the structure
of the human genome...

25
00:03:49,544 --> 00:03:51,512
<i>cure countless diseases,</i>
<i>extend human life</i>

26
00:03:51,613 --> 00:03:55,071
<i>give kids a chance to live longer,</i>
<i>stronger, healthier-</i>

27
00:03:55,183 --> 00:03:57,674
<i>Turn it offPlease</i>

28
00:03:57,786 --> 00:04:00,755
- I don't think I've explained my proposal fully.
- No, I think you have.

29
00:04:02,291 --> 00:04:04,623
Same old Reed- always stretching,
reaching for the stars...

30
00:04:04,726 --> 00:04:06,626
with the weight of the world
on his back.

31
00:04:06,728 --> 00:04:09,526
But dreams don't pay the bills,
do they?

32
00:04:10,666 --> 00:04:13,226
You remember,
when we were in school...

33
00:04:13,335 --> 00:04:15,269
we talked about working together.

34
00:04:15,370 --> 00:04:18,032
Well, that's what
I was about to explain.

35
00:04:19,141 --> 00:04:20,768
<i>The storm is deadly</i>

36
00:04:20,876 --> 00:04:23,003
<i>but the shields</i>
<i>on your station's control room</i>

37
00:04:23,111 --> 00:04:25,079
<i>are designed to protect</i>
<i>any occupants inside</i>

38
00:04:28,383 --> 00:04:32,581
So, it's not just my money you want.
It's my toys.

39
00:04:32,688 --> 00:04:37,216
<i>Tell me, if NASA doesn't trust you,</i>
<i>then why should I?</i>

40
00:04:40,529 --> 00:04:43,965
That's my job-
to stay a step ahead...

41
00:04:44,066 --> 00:04:47,729
to know what other men don't.

42
00:04:47,836 --> 00:04:50,896
- I can't take this.
- Ben, this is business. Just work.

43
00:04:51,006 --> 00:04:54,407
He's right, Ben-
It is just business.

44
00:04:54,509 --> 00:04:57,603
<i>I think you both know</i>
<i>my director of genetic research</i>

45
00:04:57,713 --> 00:04:59,613
<i>Susan Storm</i>

46
00:05:02,417 --> 00:05:04,817
One more thing he's got.

47
00:05:04,920 --> 00:05:07,013
<i>- Hey, Susie</i>
- Hey.

48
00:05:07,122 --> 00:05:10,683
Oh, it's so nice to see you.
How's Debbie?

49
00:05:10,792 --> 00:05:12,692
- Great.
- Great.

50
00:05:12,794 --> 00:05:16,662
- Uh, how have you been?
- Never better.

51
00:05:19,267 --> 00:05:21,531
- This isn't gonna be a problem, is it?
- Oh, not at all.

52
00:05:21,636 --> 00:05:23,763
- No, l-
<i>- Good</i>

53
00:05:23,872 --> 00:05:25,772
Then you are just in time...

54
00:05:25,874 --> 00:05:27,967
to hear the great Reed Richards...

55
00:05:28,076 --> 00:05:30,044
ask <i>me</i> for help.

56
00:05:31,947 --> 00:05:34,780
You made a lot of folks at M.I.T.
Feel like a junior high science fair...

57
00:05:34,883 --> 00:05:38,284
so you'll excuse me
if I savor the moment.

58
00:05:38,387 --> 00:05:40,287
You back this mission...

59
00:05:40,389 --> 00:05:42,949
and I'll sign over a fair percentage
of any applications-

60
00:05:43,058 --> 00:05:46,391
The number is 75,
and its applications and patents.

61
00:05:46,495 --> 00:05:49,487
- What about his firstborn?
- Ben.

62
00:05:49,598 --> 00:05:51,498
[ Laughing ]
Come on.

63
00:05:51,600 --> 00:05:56,003
Twenty-five percent of a billion is enough
to keep the lights on a while, isn't it?

64
00:05:56,104 --> 00:05:59,505
Maybe even pay off your fourth mortgage
on the Baxter Building.

65
00:05:59,608 --> 00:06:02,406
Deal?

66
00:06:09,818 --> 00:06:13,083
Well, then, to our future.

67
00:06:15,257 --> 00:06:18,158
Together.

68
00:06:18,260 --> 00:06:21,195
It's funny how things turn out,
isn't it?

69
00:06:21,296 --> 00:06:23,856
Hilarious.

70
00:06:25,967 --> 00:06:29,459
He knew about NASA.
Maybe he made the call to shut us down.

71
00:06:29,571 --> 00:06:32,472
Ben, think about all the people
we can help if this works. Huh?

72
00:06:32,574 --> 00:06:35,441
Look, we got what we wanted.
That's enough.

73
00:06:35,544 --> 00:06:38,911
A few days in space. It'll be great.
What's the worst that can happen?

74
00:06:43,585 --> 00:06:46,782
If Reed's right, this little trip
could double our stock offerings.

75
00:06:46,888 --> 00:06:48,913
And if he's not?

76
00:06:49,024 --> 00:06:50,855
Reed's always right.

77
00:06:50,959 --> 00:06:54,292
Good thing he doesn't always know
what he's got.

78
00:06:57,799 --> 00:06:59,767
<i>[ Beeps ]

79
00:07:02,137 --> 00:07:05,038
Reed, you should know those solar winds
have been picking up speed.

80
00:07:05,140 --> 00:07:07,472
- I factored them into my coordinates.
- Right.

81
00:07:07,576 --> 00:07:09,567
Of course you did.
In theory.

82
00:07:09,678 --> 00:07:12,704
- It's a little different once you're out there.
- I can assure you-

83
00:07:12,814 --> 00:07:15,078
When are we leaving?

84
00:07:16,384 --> 00:07:18,443
I'll be scheduling the launch.

85
00:07:18,553 --> 00:07:21,454
You can call me in the morning
for resources and crew.

86
00:07:21,556 --> 00:07:24,047
- I think I remember the number.
- It's been changed.

87
00:07:27,162 --> 00:07:29,392
<i>[ Ben Clears Throat ]

88
00:07:30,699 --> 00:07:33,293
I was hoping Ben
could pilot the mission.

89
00:07:33,401 --> 00:07:35,562
We already have a pilot
on our payroll.

90
00:07:35,670 --> 00:07:39,106
But you're welcome to ride shotgun.
Remember my brotherJohnny?

91
00:07:39,207 --> 00:07:41,107
<i>##[ Rock ]

92
00:07:48,717 --> 00:07:52,175
<i>##[ Man Singing ]

93
00:07:56,057 --> 00:07:58,958
<i>- ##[ Continues ]
- Can't do it. Cannot do it.

94
00:07:59,060 --> 00:08:00,960
External S.R.B.'s,
orbital system engines.

95
00:08:01,062 --> 00:08:03,530
- It's just like the shuttle you flew-
- No!

96
00:08:03,632 --> 00:08:06,533
- I cannot take orders from the underwear model.
- Oh, come on, now.

97
00:08:06,635 --> 00:08:10,196
That wingnut washed out of NASA for
sneaking two Victoria's Secret wannabes...

98
00:08:10,305 --> 00:08:12,364
into a flight simulator.

99
00:08:12,474 --> 00:08:15,705
- Youthful high spirits.
- They crashed it into a wall.

100
00:08:15,810 --> 00:08:17,675
A flight simulator.

101
00:08:17,779 --> 00:08:21,146
When have I ever asked you to do something
you absolutely said you could not do?

102
00:08:21,249 --> 00:08:22,841
Five times.

103
00:08:22,951 --> 00:08:26,216
- I had it at four.
- Well, this makes five.

104
00:08:26,321 --> 00:08:29,119
<i>##[ Continues ]

105
00:08:34,629 --> 00:08:36,187
<i>##[ Ends ]

106
00:08:36,298 --> 00:08:38,198
<i>[ Woman On PA]</i>
<i>Attention, all personnel</i>

107
00:08:38,300 --> 00:08:40,791
<i>Commencing launch sequence</i>
<i>in six hours</i>

108
00:08:40,902 --> 00:08:43,564
[ Ben ]
I miss you already, Debs.

109
00:08:43,672 --> 00:08:45,503
<i>[ Man ]
<i>Captain on the bridge!</i>

110
00:08:47,042 --> 00:08:49,067
Digital camera- $254.

111
00:08:49,177 --> 00:08:51,645
Memory stick- $59.

112
00:08:51,746 --> 00:08:54,874
The look on your hard-ass
former C.O.'s face...

113
00:08:54,983 --> 00:08:58,851
when he finds out he's
your junior officer- priceless.

114
00:09:00,922 --> 00:09:03,220
- [ Zipper Zips ]
- [ Chuckles ] Thank you. That's so sweet.

115
00:09:03,325 --> 00:09:05,190
I can handle this ship.

116
00:09:05,293 --> 00:09:07,659
I can even handle
Mr. Blond Ambition.

117
00:09:07,762 --> 00:09:10,560
But I don't know if I should be flying
or doing <i>Swan Lake</i> in these suits.

118
00:09:10,665 --> 00:09:12,565
Who the hell came up with these?

119
00:09:12,667 --> 00:09:15,067
Victor did.

120
00:09:15,170 --> 00:09:18,936
The synthetics act as a second skin,
adapting to your body's individual needs.

121
00:09:19,040 --> 00:09:23,101
<i>See, now that means it keeps</i>
<i>the hot stuffhot and the cool stuff cool</i>

122
00:09:24,512 --> 00:09:27,072
Wow. Fantastic.

123
00:09:27,182 --> 00:09:30,583
Material made from self-regulating,
unstable molecules.

124
00:09:30,685 --> 00:09:33,051
I've been working on
a formula for this.

125
00:09:35,290 --> 00:09:37,087
Great minds think alike.

126
00:09:38,860 --> 00:09:42,057
- Here you go, Ben.
- Thanks, sweetie.

127
00:09:42,163 --> 00:09:44,131
<i>Reed</i>

128
00:10:15,997 --> 00:10:18,898
<i>[ Von Doom ]
<i>E TA until cosmic event, nine hours</i>

129
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:21,901
If you're good, maybe next time
Daddy'll let you drive.

130
00:10:22,003 --> 00:10:25,200
You keep talkin',
and there won't be a next time.

131
00:10:27,609 --> 00:10:29,509
Long way
from the projection booth...

132
00:10:29,611 --> 00:10:32,045
at the Hayden Planetarium,
isn't it?

133
00:10:34,849 --> 00:10:37,079
Yes.

134
00:10:37,185 --> 00:10:39,244
Yes, it is.

135
00:10:40,922 --> 00:10:44,323
We can monitor the cloud's approach
and observe the tests from here.

136
00:10:44,426 --> 00:10:46,326
Is it safe?

137
00:10:46,428 --> 00:10:49,420
The shields on the station
should protect us.

138
00:10:49,531 --> 00:10:52,329
- "Should"?
- What's the matter, Ben?

139
00:10:52,434 --> 00:10:54,834
Getting paranoid in your old age?

140
00:10:54,936 --> 00:10:58,372
Let's start loading those samples.
Get your suit ready, Ben.

141
00:10:59,974 --> 00:11:03,535
So I see you're still doing
all the heavy lifting.

142
00:11:03,645 --> 00:11:06,637
Maybe you should have stayed in the lab.
Fieldwork never suited you.

143
00:11:06,748 --> 00:11:10,775
<i>He does the talkin'.</i>
<i>I do the walkin'. Got it?</i>

144
00:11:12,187 --> 00:11:14,155
So, take a walk, Ben.

145
00:11:14,255 --> 00:11:17,656
Actually, if you'll all excuse me,
I need to borrow Susan...

146
00:11:17,759 --> 00:11:19,522
<i>for a moment</i>

147
00:11:23,465 --> 00:11:25,365
Sure.

148
00:11:27,836 --> 00:11:30,737
Please tell me your guy's not trying
to rekindle things with my sister again.

149
00:11:30,839 --> 00:11:33,069
Of course not.
It's strictly business.

150
00:11:33,174 --> 00:11:36,234
Yes, well, his eyes
say differently, don't they?

151
00:11:36,344 --> 00:11:39,336
Hey. Two hearts
got busted last time.

152
00:11:39,447 --> 00:11:41,347
Maybe she's not over it either.

153
00:11:41,449 --> 00:11:43,383
Wow, Dr. Phil, that's deep.

154
00:11:43,485 --> 00:11:45,885
Let's think about that.

155
00:11:45,987 --> 00:11:49,479
<i>You got Victor-</i>
<i>more money than God, stud of the year-</i>

156
00:11:49,591 --> 00:11:52,492
and you got Reed,
world's dumbest smart guy...

157
00:11:52,594 --> 00:11:54,494
worth less than a postage stamp.

158
00:11:54,596 --> 00:11:56,496
That's a real toss-up.

159
00:11:56,598 --> 00:11:58,532
Don't trouble your tiny little mind.

160
00:11:58,633 --> 00:12:00,999
Don't wander off now, boy.

161
00:12:02,604 --> 00:12:05,835
- [ Beeping ]
<i>- [ Computer ] Securing air lock chamber</i>

162
00:12:24,225 --> 00:12:27,126
Surprised I agreed to Reed's proposal?

163
00:12:27,228 --> 00:12:29,526
I understand the business reasons.

164
00:12:30,698 --> 00:12:33,292
Well, when you're
looking at your future...

165
00:12:33,401 --> 00:12:35,801
it doesn't hurt
to find closure about the past.

166
00:12:38,473 --> 00:12:43,501
Susan, every man dreams he'll meet
a woman he can give the world to.

167
00:12:43,611 --> 00:12:47,274
In my case,
it's not just a metaphor.

168
00:12:49,317 --> 00:12:51,148
[ Beeps ]

169
00:12:51,252 --> 00:12:54,221
<i>[ Computer ]
<i>Opening viewing station shield</i>

170
00:13:20,782 --> 00:13:23,273
[ Beeping ]

171
00:13:23,384 --> 00:13:26,410
That can't be right.

172
00:13:26,521 --> 00:13:31,458
<i>[ Computer ] Event threshold</i>
<i>in T-minus nine minutes, 47 seconds</i>

173
00:13:31,559 --> 00:13:34,255
<i>[ Reed ] That's impossible</i>
<i>It should be seven hours</i>

174
00:13:38,399 --> 00:13:40,333
We've been together
two years now.

175
00:13:40,435 --> 00:13:42,926
It's been a good two years, Victor.

176
00:13:43,037 --> 00:13:45,130
The company's accomplished so much.

177
00:13:45,240 --> 00:13:47,731
Right. Of course. The company.

178
00:13:47,842 --> 00:13:49,810
But I've come to realize...

179
00:13:49,911 --> 00:13:53,847
that all the accomplishments in the world
mean nothing without someone
to share them with.

180
00:13:53,948 --> 00:13:58,647
- Um-
- I've lived my life unafraid of taking big steps.

181
00:13:58,753 --> 00:14:02,689
- Now it's time to take the biggest step of all.
- Victor-

182
00:14:02,790 --> 00:14:06,157
If it helps,
think of this as a... promotion.

183
00:14:06,261 --> 00:14:08,525
Victor, l-

184
00:14:08,630 --> 00:14:10,996
I have four words.

185
00:14:11,099 --> 00:14:14,000
Four little words that can change
our lives forever.

186
00:14:14,102 --> 00:14:16,297
<i>[ Reed ]
<i>The cloud is accelerating!</i>

187
00:14:16,404 --> 00:14:18,702
We've got minutes until it hits,
not hours.

188
00:14:18,806 --> 00:14:23,140
<i>- Victor, that storm is deadly We need to abort</i>
<i>- Get a grip, Reed</i>

189
00:14:23,244 --> 00:14:26,839
We didn't come all this way to lose our nerve
at the first glitch. Just close the shields.

190
00:14:26,948 --> 00:14:28,848
- Ben is still out there.
- So reel him in.

191
00:14:28,950 --> 00:14:33,819
<i>We came here to do a job,</i>
<i>so let's do it Quickly</i>

192
00:14:33,922 --> 00:14:37,414
Victor, Reed's right.
We have less than six minutes.

193
00:14:40,028 --> 00:14:42,690
- Ben, get inside now!
- What's going on?

194
00:14:42,797 --> 00:14:45,061
I ain't done arrangin'
your flowers yet, egghead.

195
00:14:45,166 --> 00:14:47,657
<i>[ Reed ]
<i>Ben, turn around</i>

196
00:14:56,778 --> 00:14:59,110
- [ Ben ] Guys, I'm not gonna make it.
- You gotta jump!

197
00:14:59,213 --> 00:15:01,408
<i>It's the only way!</i>

198
00:15:05,486 --> 00:15:07,078
<i>- What are you doing?</i>
- Closing the shields.

199
00:15:07,188 --> 00:15:09,713
- You can't just leave them out there.
- Watch me.

200
00:15:11,059 --> 00:15:13,425
You can't help them
any more than I can!

201
00:15:13,528 --> 00:15:15,996
I can try.

202
00:15:30,478 --> 00:15:33,606
Come on, Ben! You got this!

203
00:15:35,083 --> 00:15:37,051
Johnny, get ready to close the portal.

204
00:15:42,056 --> 00:15:43,990
[ Groaning ]

205
00:15:58,039 --> 00:16:00,234
[ Yelling ]

206
00:16:01,743 --> 00:16:03,711
[ Yelling ]

207
00:16:47,304 --> 00:16:52,936
<i>- [ Beeping ]
- [ Groans ]

208
00:16:58,916 --> 00:17:01,384
[ Groans ]

209
00:17:03,554 --> 00:17:04,555
- You okay?
- Oh. Yeah.

210
00:17:04,555 --> 00:17:06,716
- You okay?
- Oh. Yeah.

211
00:17:08,993 --> 00:17:12,827
Ben! Ben!

212
00:17:14,899 --> 00:17:17,231
Ben!

213
00:17:22,173 --> 00:17:25,142
<i>[ Monitor Beeping ]

214
00:17:27,711 --> 00:17:30,441
<i>Wake up Ben</i>

215
00:17:30,548 --> 00:17:33,449
Hey, rise and shine, big boy.
How you feeling?

216
00:17:33,551 --> 00:17:36,679
<i>- [ Groans ] Where am I?</i>
- Back on Earth.

217
00:17:36,787 --> 00:17:39,187
We're in quarantine.
Victor's medical facility.

218
00:17:39,290 --> 00:17:41,190
<i>Reed? Sue?</i>

219
00:17:41,292 --> 00:17:44,693
Oh, they're fine.
Everybody else is fine.

220
00:17:44,795 --> 00:17:46,695
<i>What's wrong with me?</i>

221
00:17:48,365 --> 00:17:51,266
I swear to you, Ben, they've done
everything humanly possible.

222
00:17:51,368 --> 00:17:54,769
The best plastic surgeons in the world
are here, Ben. You had the best.

223
00:17:54,872 --> 00:17:58,035
<i>- Give me that mirror</i>
- I don't know if that's a good idea.

224
00:17:58,142 --> 00:18:01,043
- They said the shock alone-
<i>- I said, give me that goddamn mirror!</i>

225
00:18:01,145 --> 00:18:04,603
Okay, Ben.
Just be strong.

226
00:18:09,053 --> 00:18:11,072
<i>Unfortunately, the doctors just</i>
<i>couldn't do anything to fix your face</i>

227
00:18:11,072 --> 00:18:11,936
<i>Unfortunately, the doctors just</i>
<i>couldn't do anything to fix your face</i>

228
00:18:13,240 --> 00:18:15,868
[ Yells ]

229
00:18:17,845 --> 00:18:20,279
Hey. Nice do.

230
00:18:20,380 --> 00:18:22,644
[ Chuckles ]
Likin' the grandpa look.

231
00:18:22,749 --> 00:18:24,717
What?

232
00:18:32,526 --> 00:18:36,121
<i>[ TV: Reporter ] You've been charged</i>
<i>with moving science a little too fast</i>

233
00:18:36,230 --> 00:18:38,061
[ Von Doom ]
By whom, my competitors?

234
00:18:38,165 --> 00:18:40,065
<i>[ Door Closes ]

235
